article.headline: Riley's perfect early as Shock shoot down Comets
article.linkText: Riley's perfect early as Shock shoot down Comets
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Ruth Riley made her first seven shots and
finished with 16 points to lead the Detroit Shock to a 66-60 win
over the Houston Comets on Sunday.

Deanna Nolan added 11 points and helped the Shock end Houston's
nine-game, home-winning streak. The Shock earned their first
victory in seven trips to Houston.

Sheryl Swoopes scored 14 points for the Comets, who hadn't lost
at home since a season-opening defeat to San Antonio on May 21.

Riley didn't miss a shot until there was 2:05 left in the third
quarter and finished 8-for-12.

"My play largely depends on my teammates," Riley said. "When
Cheryl Ford is double-teamed like she was today, that leaves me
open and my job then is to make the open shots.

"When they double-team the guards, I have to be ready. It's
nice to be on the receiving end of that kind of defense."

Ford was held to three points.

Misty Williams added a career-high 12 points for the Comets, who
have lost three straight for the first time this season.

Williams' previous high for the season came at Sacramento on May
25 when she scored four points. She only scored four more since
then before Sunday.

"When you are given an opportunity, you have to take full
advantage of it," Williams said. "I have been waiting for this
chance and it came today.

"Every time I go out on the court, I am looking to become a
better player."

The Shock built an 18-point lead in the first five minutes of
the third quarter as Nolan scored six points during an 8-2 run.

But the Comets, led by Williams' six points in the fourth
quarter, got back in the game and closed within 62-58 with 2:15
left. Nolan hit a 12-foot jump shot with 1:50 remaining to push
Detroit's advantage to six.

"You're always concerned when you're losing a big lead like
that on the road," Shock coach Bill Laimbeer said. "But we made
the big shots when we had to and came away with a very big win. Our
defense came through."

In the final three minutes of the first quarter, the Comets
rallied to take their only lead behind six straight points by
Swoopes.

The Comets, playing without injured starters Tina Thompson and
Dominique Canty, led 18-16 before Swin Cash made a pair of free
throws in the closing seconds to tie it after one period.

Detroit's defense then took over and allowed only one Houston
field goal in the first seven minutes of the second period. The
Shock outscored the Comets 24-12 in the second quarter and led
42-30 at halftime.

"When a team is down like they are with the injuries, it is
important to keep them there," Nolan said. "We needed this one
especially going into the All Star break."
